How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input:Learning languages is difficult.  Even in a full immersion environment you're likely to make mistakes, mistakes will cause misinterpretation, which will be uncomfortable, which will cause what?, Choices:  A: better communication B: overthinking C: frustration D: misunderstandings E: headaches<n>Output:		E<n><n>### Instruction:Read and answer the question.<n><n>Learning languages is different than learning math.  When you are learning math, you have a well defined set of facts.  They are well defined, because other people who have learned the same math agreed on them.  Agreement in mathematical concepts are built up over time through thousands of years of cooperation.  When you learn math, you often memorize sets of facts, and can apply them automatically.  If you memorize and understand 100 basic math facts, you can generally do most math problems you run into. <n><n>When you learn a language, people who have learned it before disagree on which facts are important, some facts are more important than others, and some are considered more important than they actually are.  The process of learning a language is much more like learning history than it is like learning math.  We don't have thousands of years to agree on which set of facts we think are important.  The facts constantly change based on technology, and what those who previously agreed were important. We have to be willing to challenge previously accepted ideas, and be capable of thinking out of what most people would consider to be our comfort zone; even to the point of being willing to challenge what most others consider to be common sense.<n><n>If you think in terms of what other people think is common sense, you'll be unable to think out of the box, and this will lead you to make more mistakes in your approach to language, and not less; especially in the beginning. It takes time to learn, but you need to be willing to learn new things, and be willing to challenge what many would consider to be common sense in order to do so.<n><n>It is the people who are willing to challenge what others consider to be common knowledge, and do things differently than they are "supposed" to be done that have been rewarded with success.<n><n>### Instructions:Read the question.<n><n>You have to be willing to be a little uncomfortable, and consider many things.<n><n>### Your answer:<n><n>## Instructions:Complete the sentence.<n><n>The biggest mistake newbies tend to make in the first month of learning a language is....<n><n>### Your Answer:<n><n>Challenging the unchallenged, questioning what others say is wrong, and being willing to apply your logical reasoning.<n>

How many total arrangements remain (total card pairs remaining)?<n>Output: 1320<n>"""<n><n>import re<n><n>from collections import Counter<n>def numb_in_str(txt,n):<n>    for i, char in izip(n, txt):<n>        if char==0 :return i<n>    m=re.match(r'(..(?=.))|[^0-9]|\[|\]|,|:|-|\.|\+|\$|\/|\*)', txt)<n>    return int(m.group(n))<n>def main(T):<n>    b=str(int(eval(input("input: "))))<n>    for i in b:<n>        if i in ['+','-']:continue<n>        tmp=b[:i]<n>        l=[int(ch) for ch in tmp.split('')]<n>        print(l)<n>        print(tmp)<n>        print(b[i+1:])<n>        x=numb_in_str(%s,l[-1])<n>        print(x)<n>print(counter_in_line())<n>    return<n>    def counter_in_line():<n>        s=input()<n>        tmp=s.split('')<n>        l=[int(_) for _ in tmp]<n>        tmp=l[-1]<n>        x=num_in_seq(*l)<n>        s=x+tmp<n>        print(l,x,s)<n>        return<n>if __name__=="__main__":<n>    main(input())<n>

Seed Plants <n><n>Input: The sum of the first 5 odd  positive integers is the same as the sum of the first 10 odd positive integers.  What is the sum of the numbers?<n>Output: 1555<n><n>Input: On the day of the parade, there were more than 300 decorated cars, 385 walking units, 71 riding units, and 18 drum and bugle groups.  The total number of people in these groups was 9552.  How many more people were in the parade than in the walking units?<n>Output: 9552<n><n><n><n>#### Instruction: Answer the following multiple choice question using code<n>```<n>class Solution:<n>    def maxArea(self, height: List[int]) -> int:<n>        left, right, top, bottom = 0, len(height)-1, len(height)-1, 0<n>        <n>        sum = [0] * (len(height)+1) <n>            for i in range(len(height)):<n>                sum[top] = sum[left]+height[i]<n>                top -= 1<n>                sum[bottom] = sum[right]+height[i]            <n>                right += 1<n>            max_area = max(sum)<n>        return max_area<n>    <n>    def maxAreas(self, heights: List[int])-> List[int]:<n>        result = [] <n>        answer = self.maxArea(heights)<n>        result.append(answer)<n><n>        return result<n>```<n>Output: [2.800000014901161, 2.480000220651061]

The cows are drinking 1.5 gallons of water per minute whereas 12 sheep are drinking 0.5 gallons of per minute. How much time does it take for sheep to drink the same amount of water which the cows drinks in 1 minute? <n>### Instruction<n>Instructions to write the program in this method is explained below:<n><n>Create an empty string, x<n>Create a new empty string, y<n>Print x<n>Initialize the variable time with an empty string<n>Initialize the variables to count cows and sheep<n>Loop cows and sheep = 0<n><n>Create a for loop and run it for (number of cows) cows<n>For loop cows = 0<n>Print time with a space after the time<n>Print x  <n>Increment the value by one<n><n>Run the loop for sheep<n>Loop sheep = 0 <n>Print time with a spaced after the time<n>Increment the value with 1<n><n>Run for loop till either cows or Sheep is 0<n>If cows is greater than sheep, run loop for
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. How many hours did filling the truck take?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Elijah drank 8.5 pints of coffee yesterday. Emilio drank 9.5 pints of water yesterday. (the more rare, the more expensive the calories are)   7. 2500 Euros - The class raised 2500 euros for UNICEF   8. 20% Solution - The class was able to name every country and its president who use the Spanish alphabet. He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input: Every day Tom drinks 5 12-oz cans of soda plus 64 ounces of water. How many ounces of fluid does he drink a week?<n>Output: 868<n><n>Input: Stella and Twinkle are filling up a truck with a capacity of 6000 stone blocks at the rate of 250 blocks per hour per person. They work for four hours and are then joined by 6 other people who also work at the same rate. How many hours did filling the truck take?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Elijah drank 8.5 pints of coffee yesterday. Emilio drank 9.5 pints of water yesterday. How many cups of liquid did the two boys drink yesterday?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Doris works at the Widget Factory in the packing department. She puts 3 widgets in each carton, which are 4 inches wide, 4 inches long, and 5 inches tall. She then packs those cartons into a shipping box before sending it to the loading bay. The shipping boxes are 20 inches wide, 20 inches long, and 20 inches high. How many widgets get shipped in each shipping box?<n>Output: 300<n><n>Input: Queenie earns $150 a day as a part-time clerk. She earns an additional $5 per hour as overtime pay. How much will Queenie receive for working 5 days with 4 hours overtime?<n>Output: 770<n><n>Input: Jodi starts off walking 1 mile a day for 6 days a week.  On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week.  How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input:Where would there be many people sitting in chair and listening to religious speech? Choices:  A: auditorium B: office C: synagogue D: confession E: church<n>Output:		synagogue<n><n>Input: The following is a probability distribution of heights for a certain species: * 8% shorter than 3 feet; *5% shorterthan 3 feet and 4 inches; * 2% shorter than 3'5’’; *0.5% shorter than 4' and 9% shorterthan that; *5% shorter than 5’ and 16% shorterthan that;  *2% shorterthan 5’1 1/4’’; ***5% shorter than 6 feet; * 0.05% shorter than 7 feet; * 0 - 0.15% shorter than 8 feet; * 0% between 9 and 10 feet; * 0-1% between 11 and 12 feet; * 0~ 1%between 13 and 15 feet; * 0 – 1 % between 16 and 20 feet. A family contains 13 children.  What is the probability that the average height of at least 2 children is less than 5'11''?<n>Output: 0.33%<n><n>Input: The average of 13 numbers is 22.4.  If we add 4 to each of these numbers, the average increases to 24.1.  What is the sum of the 13 numbers?<n>Output: 916<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. How many ounces of fluid does he drink a week?<n>Output: 868<n><n>Input: Stella and Twinkle are filling up a truck with a capacity of 6000 stone blocks at the rate of 250 blocks per hour per person. They work for four hours and are then joined by 6 other people who also work at the same rate. How many hours did filling the truck take?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Elijah drank 8.5 pints of coffee yesterday. Emilio drank 9.5 pints of water yesterday. How many cups of liquid did the two boys drink yesterday?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Doris works at the Widget Factory in the packing department. She puts 3 widgets in each carton, which are 4 inches wide, 4 inches long, and 5 inches tall. She then packs those cartons into a shipping box before sending it to the loading bay. The shipping boxes are 20 inches wide, 20 inches long, and 20 inches high. How many widgets get shipped in each shipping box?<n>Output: 300<n><n>Input: Queenie earns $150 a day as a part-time clerk. She earns an additional $5 per hour as overtime pay. How much will Queenie receive for working 5 days with 4 hours overtime?<n>Output: 770<n><n>Input: Jodi starts off walking 1 mile a day for 6 days a week.  On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week.  How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input:What is a mobile launching platform found in the ocean? Choices:  A: launch pad B: circus C: aircraft carrier D: large open area E: space station<n>Output:		c<n><n>Input: Two students, A, B and their professor C, have to take an exam, together with 100 other students who do not know which of the three is who. The teacher C randomly selects one question from a bag containing thirty questions. When the students sit down, he places a cover in front of each of them so that only they are able to see their question. They answer in writing but cannot communicate amongst themselves, A, B, C, or the teacher. Once they have answered, the students put the answers in a different bag. Finally, each student receives a mark, or grade, indicating how correct their answer was. The student with the highest mark receives an A. The second highest mark receives a B,  and so on. If the student who gets 90 points answers, what grade does C get by default?<n>Output: c<n>

How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input:What happens when someone is playing too aggressively? Choices:  A: get hungry B: laughter C: injury D: having fun E: feeling happy<n>Output:		 A<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>    def solution(A, B):<n>        #Write your Python solution below<n><n>        #1<n>        total_cost = sum([i for i in A + B])<n><n>        #2<n>        total_hours = sum([[i] for i in (A + B)])<n><n>        #3.75*580/10 = 4625 1.5*30/10 =5<n>        #5.75*450/10 =3025 1.75*20/10 =9<n><n>        #4<n>        total_cups = sum([[i]*A+[i]*B for i in (A+B)])<n><n>        '''<n>        if math.sqrt(i/2) <= i/3:<n>            total_cups = 342<n>        else:<n>            total_squares = sum([[i-2]*i])<n>            total_cuples = sum([[i+i] for i in [(2)(i-2)]])<n>        total_cuples = total_cuples / total_squares / 3<n>        total_cupper = 1/3 * (total_cuples-342)<n>        '''<n>        #5<n>        #How many people:<n>        total_people = sum([[[i] for i in A+B])])<n>        #How many hours:<n>        total_h = sum([[(i+j) for i in A] for j in B])<n>        #How much is the total number of hours for everyone (i.e., the total_hours of everyone)<n><n>        #6<n>        #How many blocks (I'm not using the word blocks in the question):<n>        total_block = sum([[1] for i in A + [1] for j in B + [1] for k in (A+B+[1])])<n><n>        #7<n>        #How many pints:<n>        pint_per_day = 12<n>        total_pints = sum([((12*i)-12)%12 for i in [(14-2+1)] for x in [('soda', 'water', 'tomato')]])<n>

The shipping boxes are 20 inches wide, 20 inches long, and 20 inches high. How many widgets get shipped in each shipping box?<n>Output: 300<n><n>Input: Queenie earns $150 a day as a part-time clerk. How much will Queenie receive for working 5 days with 4 hours overtime?<n>Output: 770<n><n>Input: Jodi starts off walking 1 mile a day for 6 days a week.  On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week.  How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input:What could you put a table in if you want the table to be in your house? Choices:  A: library B: demonstration C: corner D: football ground E: rug<n>Output:		demonstration<n><n>Input: What is the capital of Canada? Choices: A: Ottawa B: Toronto C: Calgary D: Seattle E: Montreal<n>Output: Ottawa<n><n>Input: What will go to the park? Choices: 1.Mike 2.Peter 3.Peter, Mike + Joe + John<n>Output: Peter, Mike + Joe +John<n><n>Input: Are these 2 countries different? Yes: 1 Argentina 2 Chile. No: 3 Finland 4 Israel.<n>Output: Finland, Israel<n>"""<n>    <n>class Solution(object):<n>    def multipleChoice(self, questions):<n>        qs = []<n>        for q in questions:<n>            qs.append(L.question(q))<n>            ans = L.answer(q)<n>            qs.extend(L.options(ans))<n>        results = []<n>        for i in range(1, len(qs)):<n>            results.append(L.choices(qs[(i - 1) % len(qs)][-2])[0])<n>            if L.choices(q[(i - 1)]).count(results[-1]) >= L.choices(L.choices((qs[(i -2)%len(qs)])[:-1])).count(results[-2]):<n>                return results[-1]<n>        return None<n>    <n><n># TEST CASES<n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    sol = Solution()<n>    tc = """<n>    Input: What could you put a table on if you want the table on your boat? Choices: A.: deck B.: floor C.: couch D..: ceiling<n>    Output: couch<n>    <n>    Input: What is the capital city of Finland? Choices: A. Helsinki B. Oulu C. Kotka D. Turku<n>    Output: Helsinki<n>    """<n>    for line in tc.split('\n')[1:]:<n>        x = sol.multipleChoice([line])<n>        print(x)<n>```<n>   <n>

The words "the", "of", and the two-letter one "ae" don't count towards the 3-letter or 2-letter words.<n>Output: 99<n>## Solution:<n>```<n>#!/usr/bin/python<n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n>'''<n>Author - JAi<n>'''<n>###Instruction:<n><n>###Input:<n>class C:<n>    def __init__(self):<n>        self.arr = []<n>       def create_arr(self): # function to create the array which stores the number of days in a month given year and month<n>            days = []<n>            for i in range(1,13):<n>                if i < 31 then<n>                    days.append(i)<n>                else:<n>                    break<n>            return days<n>    def get_min(self, year, month):<n>        # to get min of given month<n>        return days[min(1,4,6,9,11,14,16,19,21,24,26):] # 1 based indexing<n><n><n>    def get_max(self,year,month):# to get maximum number of days with given year and month<n>        return days[:-1-min(1,4)]#1 based indexing<n><n>    <n>    def get_average(self,year, month):# function to get average days of a month<n>        <n>        return (self.get_max(year, month)+self.get_min(year, month))/2<n>        <n><n>C(2021, 8).create_arr()<n>```<n># Python Question- <n><n>  1.What will be the output of the following statement?<n><n>    a.a = 1.00000098<n>    print(a)<n><n>  2.What will be the equivalent of the following line in the Python?<n><n>    for i in range(5):<n>        a = 0<n><n>print(sum(a))<n>

It consists of two numbers separated by an addition symbol (+). The symbol between the two numbers is +.  Write one line of code per mathematical expression.<n><n>If the addition symbol is not between two numbers, the expression is valid. If two numbers in the expression are less than zero, both of the numbers must be negative in order for the expression to be valid.<n><n>The mathematical expressions are number-sequences where the numbers to the right of the addition symbol are greater than or equal to the numbers to the left of the addition symbol.  The numbers may be of different types as long as they are a sequence of numbers.<n><n>For example, the expression “6 + 6” is valid.  However, the expression “4 – 6” is not valid since it is between two different numbers “4” and “6”.<n><n>Note that an expression is allowed to have a negative starting number.<n><n>Input: x+x<n><n>Output: 4*x*x<n><n>Input: 3**2<n><n>Output: 9+9<n><n>Input: 5*7<n><n>Output: 35

Choices:  A: music store B: dance hall C: orchestra D: symphony E: tennessee<n>Output:		A:music store <n><n><n>### Instruction:<n><n>If "the number of goals scored in football game against Barca by one player last season accounts for 30% of all goals in the same period, if the number of goals that could be scored by the current player is twice higher, calculate the number of goal the player can score.<n><n><n>### Solution:<n>#### Input : number of goals scored<n><n>We first multiply the number of goals scored by the team ( 6 )<n>`16 = 19/3`<n>That means that we have :<n>`16 * X > 19 *3`<n>We can eliminate X with a little rearrangement to get<n>`8*(3X+1) > 19*3`<n>This means that 8 times the number of goals scored are bigger than 19 multiplied by the number of goals that were scored by the team.<n><n>The variable we are looking for is `X` or number of goals scored, we do in the expression twice and we end on that the variable that we were looking X is equal to half of the number of goals that the team scored.<n><n>`4*(3X+1)`<n><n>`16`<n><n>### Solution A<n><n>#### Input : The number of goals scored by exactly two players last soccer season accounts for 18% of all goals in that period. The number of goals scored can be at the most 200 times the number of goals that one player scored and 280 times the number of the second goal. What are the goals scored by two players?<n><n>It is the same kind of problem as above.<n>But before, we could just multiply the team's number of goals by `2` without any changes.<n>We have to find the same X as above but `2X+1`.<n>For to solve the problem, we use :<n>`2X+1 > 200 * 280`<n><n>That is<n><n>`2X+ 2X> 200*280`<n>`4X> 56000`<n>`X> 56`<n><n><n><n>

On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week. Choices:  A: boat B: ocean C: pond D: end of line E: ocean<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: What makes a tiger different from an ant? Choices: 1. It climbs trees. 2. It has antlers.<n>3. It has stripes.<n>4. It is taller.<n>Output: A 4<n><n>Input:(1+2)^3 Output:5<n><n>Input:3^2 Output: 9<n><n>Input:24^(8^(200^9)) Output:25<n><n>```python<n>def is_valid(num, n):<n>    if int(num) >= 0 and int(num) <= n:<n>        return True<n>    return False<n>```<n>```python<n>def calculate_summation(num, n): <n>    num_base = 0<n>    num_index = 0<n>    power = 3<n>    while num_index!= n: <n>        if is_valid(num_base, power): <n>            num_index += 1 <n>            while not is_valid(num.pop(), power): <n>                pow = pow + 1<n>            num_base = pow<n>        num_base = num_base^0<n>        power = power+1<n><n>    return num_base<n>```<n>   <n><n>

How much he pays now for the gas?<n>- Input: The number of goals in a season against Barca by two players is 20% of goals scored during the season.  If the two players have an equal number of goals and the total number of these goals is 300 in the tournament, how many goals for each player scored? <n>- Input : Stella and Twinkle is filling the truck with stones capacity of 5000 stone blocks per hour per person.  They work at the rate of 500 blocks per hour, each worker.   And they're helped by 6 other people. How many hours do filling the truck took?<n>- Input : Elijah drinks 8.5 pins of coffee

There are 100 people in attendance who are members. How many more people attend who are guests?<n>Output: 200<n><n>Input;Ask the doctor if you can take the pills every 4th day.<n>Output; You should take them every 4th day<n><n>The doctor's question is "Is it OK for me to take the pills every fourth day?", the only two choices being: Yes, or No. (Yes is correct but there could be other possible answers such as Maybe)<n><n>We're assuming that the doctor only wants a Yes or No answer.<n><n>If there is more than one right answer then this is ambiguous. If an answer is wrong the program could loop through forever.<n><n>For example, if the doctor asks you "If I were to give you some magic powder right now, where would you put it?" it's ambiguous whether it is intended to only accept places that aren't illegal or not.<n><n>The doctor'd reply could also be a yes or no answer:<n><n>Doctor: "It should only be taken every fourth day. Can you remember that?"<n><n>Things that should return a Yes:<n><n>Telling the doctor that you do remember. "Yes, I remember"<n><n>Telling the patient to take the medication "every fourth day"<n><n>Everything else would be a no.<n><n>Saying "yes", after the doctor asks you to take the medication every fourth day, does not work as the doctor wants to know if the patient is going to remember, not answer the question in general.<n><n>Incorrect answers are things that the doctor would say "no" or "no no".<n><n><n>Example 1: Doctor: "You should take them every 3rd day"<n>patient: "But I'm only allowed to take them every 4 days"<n>Doctor: "Your answer is incorrect but please tell me why you think so."<n>patient: "Because I was told to take them every 3 days."<n>doctor: "Your answer should be correct, please try again."<n><n>Example 2: Doctor: "Would you rather take the medication every 3 days or every 5 days?"<n>patient: "Every 5 days"<n>Doctor:"

Choices:  A: wires B: electrical circuit C: computer network D: wall E: freeway<n>Output:		A<n><n># Solution to the above Question<n>def solution1 (n,m):<n><n>    g1=10<n>    g2=25<n>    r1=3<n>    r2=2<n>    <n>    print(max(n+1,m)/g1*r1+n/(g1**2), " ",max(n+1,-m)/g2*r2-n/(g2**2))<n><n>soln=lambda x,y:solution1(x,y)<n><n>def solution2 (n,m):  #Inputs: n, m<n>    y=5<n>    q=1<n><n>    g1,g2,r1,r2=(0,0,0,0)<n>    r1=0<n>    r2=0<n>    <n>    while y>0:<n>        if(n+y>0):<n>            print(max(n,m)/(y**2), "/ 6"," ",max(n,m)//y, "\n")<n>            print(n//y, "/ 24"," ",r1, "\n")<n>        if(q<=n/y):          <n>            r2=int(n/y)<n>            print(n/y," / ",y," / ",x, " / ",r2)<n>            q+=1<n>        elif(r1<=n):<n>            print(n," / ",y," \n")<n>            g2=y<n>            g1=g2<n>            y=x<n>            r1=n<n>            <n>soln=lambda n,m:solution2(n,m)

The output answer is 4 instead of 480 because for question number 4, it states that it's an input that the price of a bottle of fuel increased to two times the previous price of the fuel. If the price for a bottle of fuel was $200 then the new price for a bottle should be 400 and the answer should be 40. If the price for the fuel was $20 then then answer for question 4 should be 4. This is because there's a 500% increase instead of a 100% increase from fuel prices. So the next time when there is an increase of 20% you should increase it to 2 times the previous increase which is 4 times

It typically lasts about 4 years.<n><n>Input: How many times does the average pair make love in a year?<n>Output: 1<n><n>## Instruction:Write a Python program that finds if a given positive integer can be divided by itself.<n>```python<n>#!/usr/bin/python<n># This code is part of the Hour of Code challenge tutorial<n># Parts of this challenge will be shown or explained during the tutorial<n><n>class DivDivOne(object):<n>    """Given an int, this class checks whether the int can<n>    be divided by itself."""<n><n>    def check(self, n):<n>        """Check whether n can be diveded by itself.<n>        :param n: an int to check<n>        :return: bool (True if n can be divided by itself,<n>        False otherwise).<n>        """<n>        num = n<n>        while num < 0:<n>            num *= -1<n>        if num == 1:<n>            return True<n>        elif num % num == 0:<n>            return True <n>        else:<n>            return False<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    n = DivDivOne()<n>    print n.check(6) # True<n>    print n.dividedbyone(18) # False<n>    print n.checkediv(536) # True<n>```

Bones<n>Output: A<n>#!/bin/python3<n><n>from sys import stdin<n>from io import StringIO<n>import re<n><n>def read_lines(lines=True):<n>    input = bytes(stdin.buffer.read(), encoding='latin-1')<n>    if not lines: return [input]<n>    if input=="\r":<n>        input="."<n>    return [input]<n><n>def get_int(input_string, default=0, min=None, max=None):<n>    def get(value, min, max):<n>        if value == -1:<n>            return "" if not min else min<n>        if value == 1:<n>            return "1"<n>        if value == None:<n>            return ""<n>        if not max or value < max:<n>            return "" + str(value)<n>        if not min or value > min:<n>            return "-" + str(abs(min - value))<n>        if value >= 1 and value <= max-min:<n>            return str(value)<n><n>    number = re.search(r'.*?([0-9]+)', input_string)<n>    if not number: return ""<n>    return '"' + get(int(number.group(1)), min, max) + '"'<n><n>def get_list(input_string, pattern):<n>    def getstr_int(value, min, int_max):<n>            if value == -1 or value == int_max:<n>                return None<n><n>            if int_max == 0:<n>                return None if value < 0 else value<n><n>            if value == 0:<n>                 return "0" if value < 0<n>            if int_min!= int_max:<n>            if value == None or value == int_min:<n>                return None #00001234 or.*?[0-

The player who hits the most monkeys wins.<n>2. The winning player can continue to play a game if they manage to hit the monkey that they had already hit before.<n><n>If you manage to hit the same monkey twice in one go, it should trigger the first rule (the player has made the most hits). In that case, you win the round, but you do not get any reward. <n><n>You get reward for hitting each monkey only once. If you have already hit a monkey and you hit it for second time in a row, it should print "You already hit this one and have not received reward". <n><n>Every player starts with a score of 0.<n><n>If you hit and kill a monkey, it should print "Killed: " and the number of the killed monkey as well as your score will both increase by one.<n><n>The program must have a score counter, a list of monkeys and all input must come from the keyboard and only two monkeys can be killed per game. <n><n>Monkeys should be ordered according to numbers: 1-3 - african monkeys, 4-6 – aasian monkeys and 7-9 - european monkeys. This list only contains names of monkeys as they are in game, they should appear like:<n><n>1: african monkey<n>2: african monk<n>3: african mon<n>4:

Choices:  A: sickness B: motion sickness C: relocation D: jet lag E: fatigue<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: Tasha ate 85% of her entire pack. Tasha was then rehired because she accidentally broke the other 400% of the pack. What is the remainder of her food?<n>Output: 25%
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. They work for four hours and are then joined by 6 other people who also work at the same rate. How many hours did filling the truck take?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Elijah drank 8.5 pints of coffee yesterday. Emilio drank 9.5 pints of water yesterday. How many cups of liquid did the two boys drink yesterday?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Doris works at the Widget Factory in the packing department. She puts 3 widgets in each carton, which are 4 inches wide, 4 inches long, and 5 inches tall. She then packs those cartons into a shipping box before sending it to the loading bay. The shipping boxes are 20 inches wide, 20 inches long, and 20 inches high. How many widgets get shipped in each shipping box?<n>Output: 300<n><n>Input: Queenie earns $150 a day as a part-time clerk. How much will Queenie receive for working 5 days with 4 hours overtime?<n>Output: 770<n><n>Input: Jodi starts off walking 1 mile a day for 6 days a week.  On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week.  How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input:Where is a likely place to view an old copy machine? Choices:  A: industrial area B: museum C: barn D: school E: office<n>Output:		A (Industrial Area)<n><n><n>### Solution<n><n>```python<n>def solution(input_1):<n>#!/bin/python<n><n>def answer(input_1): #Define answer function<n>    if input_1 == "soda": #If user's answer doesn't match "soda", return False<n>        return False <n>    else: #else, return True<n>        return True<n>    <n>if __name__ == "__main__": # if you're running this file as a script, do following in main function.<n>        if answer(input_1) == False: <n>            print('false')<n>        else:<n>            print('true')<n>```<n><n><n>```python<n>import timeit, sys<n><n>for i in range(0, 8): #for loop to test eight answers in an inbuilt function<n>    ans = answer(sys.argv[i+1]) #answer function<n>    print('running time: {:.3f} sec'.format(timeit.Timer('ans = answer(sys.args[i + 1])', number = 100000).timeit(number = i+1)))  #for timeit<n>```<n><n><n>![](/img/answer_function.png)  #Time it ran<n><n><n><n><n><n>### Source Code<n>https://github.com/s108910090/leetcodeproblems/tree/master/python<n><n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. The shipping boxes are 20 inches wide, 20 inches long, and 20 inches high. How many widgets get shipped in each shipping box?<n>Output: 300<n><n>Input: Queenie earns $150 a day as a part-time clerk. She earns an additional $5 per hour as overtime pay. How much will Queenie receive for working 5 days with 4 hours overtime?<n>Output: 770<n><n>Input: Jodi starts off walking 1 mile a day for 6 days a week.  On the second week, she walks 2 miles a day, 6 days a week.  On the third week, she walks 3 miles a day, 6 days a week. Finally on the fourth week, she walks 4 miles a day, 6 days a week.  How many miles has she walked in 4 weeks?<n>Output: 60<n><n>Input:The color yellow is associated with the opposite of the characteristic, what is it? Choices:  A: fearless B: english carrier C: courageous D: brave E: achromatic<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input:How many times is "sir" mentioned in a movie called "Jane"?  Choices: A: 26 B: 18 C: 17 D: 16 E: 15 F: not mentioned (the sir here is "sir John")<n>Output: A<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>The total cost could be calculated with the following equation: `total_cost = 0.15 * 3 + 8`<n><n>The total score for the player could be calculated with the equation `player_scores = 0.2 * 2 + 0.3 * 1 + 0.5 * 1`<n><n>The amount of liquid in the truck could be calculated with these equations:<n><n>Filling the truck takes 8*0.5 = 4 hours<n><n>The daily consumption of coffee and water is 8 + 6 = 14<n>The total amount of liquid consumed is calculated with this equation `total_liquid_consumed = daily_consumption * 5 = 42 + 288`<n><n>The number of widgets in each shipping box can be found with this equation `widgets_per_box = width = 4 + height = 5 + height = 20`.<n><n>The total number of days that Queenie was working is `(2 + 3 + 4)` = 9. She works 9 * (4 + 1) = 36 days.<n><n>The total distance Jodi walked is calculated with this equation: `distance_walked = 1*6 = 6 + 2*6 = 12 + 3*6 = 18 + 4*6= 24`<n><n>The colour bravery refers to the word brave so the option is D or E.<n>In Jane, there is one mention of the word "sir" in the third movie of the game.

The number of calories is given by `1000*(0.38 + 0.58*20)`. Notice that `20` here is in `20% of hours in a week`. The number of cardio minutes is given as `20*0.20`, assuming that `20% of cardio time in a week` and `1/5 of weightlifting time in a week` can be combined together. Let's look at the total number of calories and exercise minutes.  <n><n>- The total number of calories is `34(20*0.38)+22(20*0-200). 36`. Similarly, the total number of exercise minutes is 36 `(20+12)*0.2+6*(0.3+0.5)`. Now we solve for `480`, which is the amount of fuel cost by each of the drivers (a total of two drivers).  <n><n>- I am not sure how this question is put together.  However, we will assume that `number of goals scored in a season against Barca by 2 players` is `20%`.  We need to get the number of goals scored by each of the two players. For `20% for n goals`, we can get for `number of goals scored by each player` by `n*(100/20)`.  In this question, `n` is equal to `300` (total number of goals scored) and 2/3 is equal to `100/22`.  Therefore, the number of goals scored during the last season by each player is `2*(100/30+100/3)`. Now we solve for 30 by plugging in the value.  <n><n>-  The number of fluid ounces and cups is equivalent. When calculating the number of ounces, 1 ounce = 29 ml. Otherwise, it should return the player who has guessed the exact number of apples.<n>Examples (for 5 guess

How much did it cost him?<n>Output: ￥117<n><n>```<n>def sol1(data: str):<n>    data = int(data.replace(',', ''))<n>    p = []<n>    r = []<n>    r += [0 if data == 0 else 1]<n>    for i in range(1, len(data)):<n>        if data % 2!= 0:<n>            p.append(r[-1] % 2)<n>            r -= 1<n>        else:<n>            r += p<n>            p = p[:-1]<n>            r.append(r[-2] - (r[-1] %2))<n>

In other words, you may not use `eval` to calculate something that you could otherwise calculate using another function.<n><n>### SOLVED QUESTIONS INSTRUCTION:   <n>Include any comments or questions in the [comments](https://github.com/JenB/JavaScript-Questions/edit/master/test3/test3.txt)

This was 40% cooler than before, and the change only took 6 hours.  What was the original temperature?<n>Output:  9<n><n>Input: The sum of my daughter’s ages equals 15.
